<p style="text-align: justify;">
  It&#8217;s not uncommon to find yourself in a situation where you can&#8217;t remember the password from a blog that you have quite some time to log-on and administer. The case is that when you ask to get your password sent to your email you are stuck with a message like &#8220;The email address is not registered with a blog&#8221; (sic). To circumvent this you can use your cPanel (or any other alike platform) to get access to your WordPress database (of course this is provided that you <strong>do</strong> recall the pass to your cPanel account <img src="http://i1.wp.com/www.statsravingmad.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif?w=768" alt=";)" class="wp-smiley" data-recalc-dims="1" /> ). Then head over to your wordpress installations and check the databases name, typically they will be in the wrd_xx fashion (asearch for something like <strong>Database Connection Information</strong>). Mark it, return to cPanel and open the <strong>phpMyAdmin</strong> module. When you select the database (remember the wrd_xx ?) you will face in the main window of the module the following. At the bottom of the list you can see the <strong>wrd_users</strong>. Click on it!
</p>

<p style="text-align: justify;">
  <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" />
</p>

<p style="text-align: justify;">
  When you click it you can edit it. For example select <strong>Inline Edit</strong> and you can reset all user data you have input previously and now you don&#8217;t remember (that&#8217;s why we do all this after all).
</p>
